column9: The watermark on video 2 ruins it. The baseball cards in video 1 would probably be more interesting to fans of the web site he owns.
Video 1 is very niche oriented. While video 2 is interesting and good quality, it's not one I would share with anyone.

I think there are a lot of people who would like the jerseys review before buying from them. Also, for some reason I submitted this eval and it showed the same two videos again. I think I missed a question the first time.
Video 1 camera moved around a lot, but many people love baseball.
Video 1 is a nationally known team.
Video 1 is history in the making. Video 2 is just fireworks that could be seen any where on the 4th of July. That is why I like video 1 better.
I think Video 1 will be much more popular because I have never heard of the team in Video 2. Video 1 is also a higher quality video and the sound quality is better in Video 1.
Video 1 is more of an advertisement for that guy's store. I don't think it will be very popular. Video 2 would be better if it didn't have the Screenflow Demo watermark across it.

Screaming in the firework show is very annoying but understand it can be avoided by pressing mute.

The card evaluations was extremely boring. It would belong to a specialized niche.

I like the greatest hits kind of videos. 

I suspect this study if for ASMR because of the card evaluations have that feeling.

The second video was more euphoric, lot of epic moments.

The First video had the more personalized human feel that has OCD.
Video#2 appears to be more about post-game fireworks! - So, popularity will depend on personal preference.
Video#1 has more action appeal.
Both videos rather mediocre, not to excitable and, at times, confusing. Video#1 is, however, better organized and choreographed.
Video#1 is mostly for true enthusiasts of player cards; video#2 is a pure sports moment video.
I think video 2 will be more popular because its fireworks.
The video on the left is much more intesting (and exciting) to watch.
I enjoy a good "showing off product" video, but my friends would rather see the game video!
Fireworks always wins. The other video was pretty boring in comparison.
The first one had some funny tidbits, however the 2nd video's excitement and energy really made me love that video more!
The first video was nothing but fireworks and screaming. Awful!

Video 1 is one of the reasons I love baseball, fans get so invested in a game and the history of THE game , it wouldn't have mattered if he was pitching for the home team or not, the fans would all be standing and holding their breath with each pitch, just loving watching history.  very cool.

I actually like looking at baseball cards and checking out the stats, seeing what they looked like when they were rookies, but video 1 was pretty tedious, some things just really don't need to be filmed and shared. but - yay! Jim Rice :) As for video 2 - not cool to buy knock offs, we can't control how legit companies make their products as far as fair wages and work environment, how could we possibly know or control how the knock offs are made.

I'm a sox fan so have gotten an up close and personal look at Mariano Rivera's career, he's amazing and truly the best closer in history.  I loved his reacton to the fans at Fenway after we eon the WS and we showed him our "appreciation" for sucking for a couple of games!!  He's a class act and baseball won't be the same without him.

Video 1 didn't really share any baseball strategy or insight so you would really only care about the video if you were a fan of the team.  Video 2 was fun for the first couple of minutes but went too long, that's why i wouldn't share it.
I think vid 2 is better because its a product review instead of a commercial like vid 1
Vid 1 is better because of the variety it provides. Not all baseball fans like the Yanks
Fireworks are alway fun to watch. The guy in vid 1 is flat, not captivating at all
Vid 1 is better, good review the guy has a personality. Vid 2 is flat, would have to be a fan of the team to really enjoy the vid.
Video 2 was very painful to listen to. The narrator kept correcting himself at the beginning. Very unprofessional.
The first video was painfully boring to watch.

I would share the first video solely based on its historical significance. The camera work is not very good, but it was a perfect game. The second video strikes me as very commercial, and I would never share it with my friends.
In the first video, even the creator seems bored with his baseball cards. The second video is equally boring. The product is unremarkable, and full of defects. I would share neither of these videos.
Both are boring and uninteresting. The first one is about a team too small so it will never become popular on Youtube, and the second one is 4 minutes of fireworks. Nothing stands out.
The guy in video 2 has a nice shop with a lot of cards, but who wouldn't rather watch baseball?
I'd much rather listen to someone talk about baseball cards, even if he is tone is boring, than to someone talking about inspecting shirts. Shut up, put the shirt on, and enjoy it.
Great video & music.
Video 1 is better for information. As for video 2, fireworks are nice, but never as good on video as in person. I also don't enjoy videos of people screaming, even if it is joyful.
Video 1 was only showing fireworks after a game. I thought it would show baseball action of some sort. Seems more like comparing apples and oranges in this particular circumstance.
Video 2 seems like someone put some time into making it.
Video 1 seems like a useful review. Video 2 is okay, but not really all that baseball related even though it was recorded at a baseball game.
I found the sound of the packages of cards being opened in the second video very annoying.
Video 2 seemed very slow and dull.
Same two that I had for the first set of evaluations.

I would have ended both of these videos very early if I had the choice. The first bored me as it was just a typical ballpark fireworks display, The second would have been good, barring the watermark in the middle of the screen which makes me not want to watch at all. At least they apologized for the lag in the second video.
First was more attention grabbing, but I would be more likely to share video 2.
Video 1 was also good but you can't beat a home run video.
Sold on Video 2. I will for surely stop in next time I'm in the area.
I hate the Yankees, so I would watch grass grow before watching them.

Nothing beats a perfect game to a baseball fan, I watch Matt Cain for the Giants pitch his perfect game last year it was awesome. I also got to watch my son pitch one in college, nothing beats that feeling. But I think the fireworks might appeal to more people.
Rivera, might be the best closer in baseball to bad he did it with the Yankees. The other video is college Ball State I think major league even the Yankees would be the most popular.
I loved the jersey one because who doesn't like a bargain in clothes shopping. Getting a nice jersey cheap is great because then you can have a couple of different ones.

You almost lost me starting off the second video with a Dodger even if it is Kurt Gibson. I still liked it best with all the great home runs awesome video. The collectibles store was really cool to see.
A perfect game is so rare I would have to share.
The fireworks are just much more interesting to watch and they are playing good music.
I would diff share the best homeruns of all time.
These were both pretty boring to watch. I think it would be better if they included the value on the cards and what to look for to know the difference in values.
The left video is about actual baseball while the right video is just about baseball cards. The left video is more interesting in my opinion.
The left video is just about baseball cards and is somewhat uninteresting. The right video is about great baseball plays and is more interesting to watch.
I'm interested in baseball but not so much in cards.
The orientation of the first video is really annoying.
The first video looks like it was broadcasted on TV and it is more interesting since I actually get to see people play.
I am an avid collector of cards so of course the right is my favorite.
they guy in the left video gives me the creeps. Plus i didn't like looking up his nose for 5 minutes.
I collect cards so I like that one more but the closeout will probably be more popular
The left one was about a team I have no idea about. The right was some interesting fireworks.
Both were too long for me to share. I try and share quick and entertaining videos.

Personally I thought the one on the right was more interesting, but I think the general population would be more interested in the one on the left.  I'm not really into baseball cards or anything though.
I would enjoy watching highlights rather than people talking about cards
The 2nd video was alot more exciting than the first.
I thought video 1 was a lot more fun and interesting.
I liked video 1 because it had variety of teams and classic moments.
Pack opening videos are fun so I think video 1 will get more views.
Video 1 was fun to watch. I like pack opening videos.
both hosts are pretty good so the popularity will be determined by which topic has a wider viewing audience.
Video 2 looks 1000 times better even if its very similar content
Neither video was good. the first one was just WAY worse than the second, thus I predict the second will be more popular than the first, but still not very successful.
The person speaking in video had a much more amiable tone, which gives it a huge edge compared to the monotone speakers of the right video.
I think the left video was just more exciting. It had a little bit of suspense and really put you in the moment of the game.

I found that I wasn't interested in either video. The video on the left was about a minor league team that I've never heard of and it was just interviews with players I didn't know. The video on the right is just a guy going through a pack of baseball cards he bought, which was just really boring.

I think the video on the right was just more interesting. The left video was a nice video of fireworks, but almost all firework shows seem the same to me and they don't excite me much watching them in a video. The video on the right brings back good memories of seeing some of these homeruns as they happened though.

I think the left video is an exciting look at Mariano Rivera. It shows some highlights from one of the best closers in the game. The right video seems more like an advertisement for the card shop and doesn't really hold my interest.

The second video seemed like an advertisement, and for a store that I would never visit more than likely, so I preferred the first video. I thought the quality of the first video could and maybe should have been better, but it was exciting and interesting.

Both videos were about subjects that I don't care much about, but I thought the quality of the second video was far better than the first one, and as I watched the second video, I learned that I was actually curious about what was being said.

The quality of the presentation in the first video was laughable, to be honest, and since I'm not a baseball card collector (although I was when I was a kid), I really didn't care for that one. I really enjoyed the second video, but I didn't like the music, I didn't see how it improved the video and for me at least it was actually a distraction.

I thought the quality of both videos was relatively poor, although the first video was better overall. I really didn't care for the content of either video and I probably never would have watched either of them if I was just browsing YouTube.
Baseball memorabilia is in video one and I think that will be popular.
Who doesn't want to see the greatest home runs of all time?
None were too much about baseball. One was fireworks and the other was just baseball cards- but not the actual game of baseball.

I love watching baseball, but the song playing in video 1 is the reason I did not choose it as my favorite. Though it was semi-interesting to see the quality of jerseys purchased, I'd normally prefer to watch a game being played - sans music.
Nothing
Nothing

Nothing
Too much dead time showing last batter of a perfect game. Some appeal, as it's a rare event. Video #2 was just an ad for a baseball card store. ZERO appeal, I'd think, even for a card collector

Boring! Boring!! Boring!!! Hard to find anything else to say about them. #1 you see the guy's face and light in the background making the cards nearly unviewable, if anyone really cares to look at them. The second keeps scanning some cheap, imitation baseball jerseys. YAWN!
Limited appeal for #1 - only really for baseball card lovers. #2 has obnoxious sound inserted - definitely a detractor.

Sports interviews are universally boring - same trite evaluations over and over. Don't even know what team was being interviewed, as only their opponent was named on the video, and the air sound on the microphone only made things worse. #2, on the other hand, has appeal beyond sports fans, as it's the fireworks following a game (presumably). Not the greatest videography, but an appealing display nonetheless.

This particular baseball card video is just so bland and boring, and the collector is dry...  The perfect game video is quite interesting and worthy of watching, so I believe it will get so much more traffic, as it would take a very unique specific individual to actually sit and watch the card collector video...

First, I havent seen this particular video (#2), but I have seen almost all of the highlights, etc...  The baseball card one this time will probably get some traffic, but I believe that the postseason homeruns video will get far more traffic...

The first one was actually about baseball, the game, the players, interview style, while the other one was about baseball cards and a card shop and would probably be watched on youtube far more than the mostly unknown baseball team hightlight/interview...

Although the highlight real video is far more entertaining, in this situation I believe that the "cheap jersey" video will get far more traffic from people who are actually researching this type of information for purchase decisions...
The video of the perfect game is more exciting, and more people would be willing to watch the end of that match.
The first video was too long and too dull, more people will want to watch a video of fireworks.  Albeit a 4 minute long video of fireworks with 80's music in the background.
The first video had an annoying watermark on the front, and pop up tabs common on youtube, it was very distracting, the gap towards the end was also very annoying.
While the first video featured someone speaking slower about baseball cards, it seemed more personal- and you related more to this person who enjoys collecting baseball cards.
I enjoyed video one but I didn't like the shaky camera panning and it definitely could have been edited, even for an amateur vid.
I found the wind and background noise of the first one will distracting and detracted from watching it, I had to keep fiddling with the volume.

I chose Video 1 because the quality of the images was better than video 2, and even though I don't like baseball, the excitement of the fans made me feel like watching. There was a voice over in video 2 was so monotone and boring that it was hard to even listen to. The second video seemed a bit choppy and I didn't like how the scenes looked at times (ie, black and white, fuzzy, old).
Neither were very good but I found Video 2 to be more interesting. The voice of the guy in Video 1 was so monotone, it was hard to be interested.
They were both very boring to me. I am not interested in jerseys or hearing about baseball and neither video did anything to make the subject more interesting.

I am not a big baseball fan and don't know who Mariano Rivera is. I found Video 1 to be much more interesting and entertaining; the music, the fan reaction and the fireworks show provided more excitement for me than the clips of video 2, which I didn't relate to at all, even though I did like hearing Metallica.
I loved the fireworks and the exciting player rush at the end of both videos.  They are both pretty good overall.
Right video is much better by far!
